@WebMvcTest auto-configures Spring MVC infrastructure:
Correct, this annotation is used for Spring MVC tests and it auto-configures the necessary Spring MVC infrastructure components.

@WebMvcTest is meta-annotated with @ExtendWith(SpringExtension.class):
Correct, this annotation is used to integrate the Spring TestContext Framework with JUnit Jupiter.

@WebMvcTest auto-configures MockMvc:
Correct, this annotation provides auto-configuration for MockMvc which is essential for testing MVC controllers without starting a full HTTP server.

None of the above:
Correct, since all the other statements are accurate, the statement &#x27;None of the above&#x27; is not correct.

@Inject:
Incorrect, this is a Java standard (JSR-330) annotation that is similar to Spring&#x27;s @Autowired, used for dependency injection, not for defining beans.

@Component:
Incorrect, this annotation is used to indicate that a class is a Spring component, but it does not define a bean using Java code.

@Bean:
Correct, this annotation is used on a method to indicate that it returns an object that should be registered as a bean in the Spring application context.

@Autowired:
Incorrect, this annotation is used for automatic dependency injection, not for defining beans.

@AfterReturning:
Incorrect, this advice runs after a method returns normally and cannot suppress exceptions.

@Before:
Incorrect, this advice runs before the method execution and has no ability to suppress exceptions thrown by the method.

@AfterThrowing:
Incorrect, this advice runs after a method throws an exception, but it is used to perform actions after an exception is thrown, not to suppress it.

@Around:
Correct, an @Around advice can be used to execute code before and after the advised method is called. It can prevent the exception from propagating to the caller by catching the exception and handling it within the advice, effectively suppressing it.

@SpringBootWebController:
Incorrect, there is no such annotation in Spring Boot.

@SpringBootController:
Incorrect, there is no such annotation in Spring Boot; the correct annotation is @Controller or @RestController.

@ConfigurationProperties:
Correct, this annotation is used to bind external configuration properties to a bean.

@JsonComponent:
Correct, this annotation is used to indicate that a class is a Jackson Component and can be used to customize the way JSON is read or written.

